As @ jayb noted, new cases from China have dropped markedly. Anyone can see this from the WHO Situation Reports (https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019/situation-reports/). Needless to say, I presume an abundance of caution on the part of the CDC and some level of political pressure. Furthermore, reducing the travel advisory would imply that China looks more like Japan, that is, has returned to some degree of normalcy. That does not seem likely in the near-term. We simply do not know enough to think that a return to normalcy would not trigger a fresh wave of nw cases. @Skildr points out that the SARS travel advisory lasted 96 days. In the link he shared (https://www.cdc.gov/about/history/sars/timeline.htm), the CDC says, "CDC lifted the travel alert on Toronto because more than 30 days (or three SARS incubation periods) had elapsed since the date of onset of symptoms for the last reported case", for its actions on May 20. For May 23: "CDC reinstated travel alert for Toronto because on May 22, Canadian health officials reported a cluster of five new probable SARS cases." I think a downgrading will demand a month or so of no new cases. China could achieve that within the next 30 days, giving the DCD 30 days from then to monitor the situation, so 60 days to be sure. So, let's say the first or second week of April is a good time to think the CDC might downgrade or lift the travel notice. However, though COVID-19 has a lower mortality rate than SARS (or MERS), it is transmitted between humans much more efficiently. For that reason, localizing it is very difficult so the CDC will be weary of a fresh wave of infections from China. Of course, China has much fewer rates of new cases than the UK and Western Europe, etc and in real as opposed to official figures, it is likely to have way fewer cases than the US, but I don't think that affects how the CDC will look at China. Adding a couple of general observations to those in forecasts below:

Base rate: As part of its response to the 2003 SARS outbreak, the CDC issued issued a travel alert for all of mainland China on March 29 and removed it on July 3 [1] - meaning the alert lasted for a total of 96 days. The CDC only lifted the travel alert once "more than 30 days (or three SARS incubation periods) had elapsed since the date of onset of symptoms for the last reported case" [1].

"Level 4 – Do Not Travel" is in force, since the life threating conditions are still ongoing in China. The biggest driver is the growthrate of the Corona virus. Forinstance, The Modern Plague began in the 1860s and killed more than 12 million people in China, India and Hong Kong. It wasn’t until the 1890s that people figured out how the bacterial infection was being spread and a vaccine was created. Scientists declare how Corona virus being spread, but it is known that when the vaccine is available. Therefore, it is likely that the vaccine will take years to be developed. But it is not the only way to stop a virus such as MERS, SARS and EBOLA. So, it is likely that in 6 months, disease will stop and decrease in spreading rates. https://www.businessinsider.com/wuhan-coronavirus-vaccine-could-take-years-timeline-and-cost-2020-2 https://www.cnn.com/interactive/2014/10/health/epidemics-through-history/

@chwang has a good comment on this. The first bucket should be zero as of today, and the second is extremely unlikely in my opinion. As for the other two, sticking with 3 incubation periods before lifting the travel notice would mean the last case would have to be mid-to-late April for the "Not before 1 June 2020" threshold. That's a big maybe based on the SARS timeline and assuming Corona started in mid December.

During the 2003 SARS epidemic, the CDC did not lift its travel ban on Toronto until there were no more reported cases with symptoms for 3 incubation periods. The incubation time is currently as long as 2 weeks. Therefore, the CDC is unlikely to lift the ban to China until 6 weeks after the last case. Given the current state of uncertainty including probable under-diagnosis of the true prevalence, I suspect the China epidemic of nCoV will continue for at least 3 months. Thus, plus the 6 week monitoring period, makes late May the earliest a travel ban would be lifted. But this likelihood is low.
